postcontent:
WTS a Detonics Combat Master Mk I. .45 ACP.

This is one of the original Seattle, Washington guns -- mfg in 1976 or 77, one of the first 1000 Detonics pistols built. I purchased this from the original owner in Seattle.

It currently has the later style blued slide, barrel, and hammer, as well as the later factory checkered wood grips. Gun is in excellent condition with just the slightest bit of finish wear on the corners. Overall 90+% condition, this gun has been a safe queen with both the previous owner and me. Gun functions perfectly and shoots accurately.

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson Model 36 - .38 Special - 3" Barrel
postcontent:
The Model 36 was designed in the era just after World War II, when Smith & Wesson stopped producing war materials and resumed normal production. For the Model 36, they sought to design a weapon that could fire the more powerful .38 Special round in a small, concealable package. Since the older I-frame was not able to handle this load, a new frame was designed, which became the Smith & Wesson J-frame.
The new design was introduced at the International Association of Chiefs of Police (IACP) convention in 1950, and was favorably received. A vote was held to name the new revolver, and the name "Chief's Special" won. A three inch barreled version of this design went into production immediately, due to high demand. It was available in either a blued or nickel plated finish. [2] It was produced as the "Chief's Special" until 1957, when it then became the Model 36. The "Chief's Special" continued to be manufactured.


THIS FINE PIECE OF MACHINERY HAS A "BORN ON DATE" OF 1971 AND IS IN PRISTINE CONDITION - ABSOLUTELY BEAUTIFUL AND FULLY FUNCTIONAL!

title: For Sale:  HK USP 9mm with 15-round magazine
postcontent:
This is an exceptionally accurate handgun, has an excellent DA/SA trigger, as well as being extremely reliable. This one is used but in excellent used condition. Not interested in trades. The price is firm. 

Originally designed for the American market, the USP (Universal Self-loading Pistol) has found international acceptance as an accurate and ultra-reliable handgun. Features favored by U.S. law enforcement and military users provided much of the design criteria for the USP. The controls are uniquely American, influenced by such famous designs as the Government Model 1911 pistol.

All USPs use a fiber-reinforced polymer frame stiffened by stainless steel inserts at areas subject to stress and friction. HK pioneered this use of polymer materials in the production of handguns more than 30 years ago with the development of the VP70Z and P9S pistols.

The USP control lever, a combination safety and decocking lever, is frame mounted and quickly accessible, unlike the slide-mounted safeties common on many semi-automatic pistols.

Using a modified Browning-type action with a special patented recoil reduction system, the USP recoil reduction system reduces recoil effects on pistol components and also lowers the recoil forces felt by the shooter. This same recoil reduction system has been tested and proven in the HK Mark 23 pistol developed for the U.S. Special Operations Command. The USP recoil reduction system is insensitive to ammunition types and requires no special adjustment or maintenance. It functions effectively in all USP models.

title: For Sale:  Connecticut Valley Arms. 50 caliber muzzle loader
postcontent:
OK: here is the story on this rifle!

This rifle does have some scratches and missing finish (it does have a wooden stock), but it was like that when I bought it. 

A friend of mine needed cash and I was working then so I gave him $100.00 for the rifle and thought I was getting a good deal! Then I discovered the open sights were missing, they had to be ordered from Connecticut Valley Arms $35.00 Plus S/H around $40.00, plus the ram rod was also gone. I bought a fiberglass rode with brass ends at WalMart for $25.00 making $175.00 in the rifle.

Several of my buddies had muzzle loaders and I just did not like the raw powder (it spilt everywhere) and having to lube the patch before inserting the ball, forget it.  I found some 250 grain bullets & sabots (I think) at WalMart, these were new to the market at the time and I believe I gave $21.00 or $22.00 for them. The bullets came with 50 grain Proxed powder pellets.

I have shot it a couple of times but really don’t have the sights fine-tuned yet. After shooting the rifle a couple of times I was impressed enough that I went back and went back and bought a packs of 300 grain bullet’s & sabots (My wife’s uncle has seen Elk on his farm and I was hoping to use these to harvest one).

There are 11 of the 250 grain bullets & sabots left and 18 of the 50 grain Proxed powder pellets left (9 shots at 100 grains of powder). 

After buying the bullet’s & sabots I discovered that the #11 percussion caps that came on the rifle were not hot enough to ignite the pellets reliability, so I have replaced it with a bigger / hotter # 10 nipple. 

There is one on the rifle and two new ones still in the pack, along with a new box of CCI #10 percussion caps (might be 6 or 8 missing). 

Other accessories:

This rifle has quick disconect sling swivel studs mounted / made on the rifle, a Black Powder cleaning kit, plus an old military pouch I use for a possible bag along with a zippered camo rifle carrying case made by Allen Co.

Another thing I was planning to do; once I had the bullet and powder charge figured out I was going to cut the plastic tubes (the bullets and powder are in) to make a reload tube for a quick second shot. 

I had also planned on re-finishing the stock when I got it shooting like I wanted but as with most plans of mad; sickness and heart surgery curtailed them rather quickly. The best I can figure I have between $240.00 and $250.00 invested.

I can send more photos.

title: For Sale:  HK USP .45 in used excellent condition
postcontent:
This is an exceptionally accurate handgun, has an excellent DA/SA trigger, as well as being extremely reliable. This one is used but in excellent used condition. Comes with 1 10-round magazine. Not interested in trades. 

Originally designed for the American market, the USP (Universal Self-loading Pistol) has found international acceptance as an accurate and ultra-reliable handgun. Features favored by U.S. law enforcement and military users provided much of the design criteria for the USP. The controls are uniquely American, influenced by such famous designs as the Government Model 1911 pistol.

All USPs use a fiber-reinforced polymer frame stiffened by stainless steel inserts at areas subject to stress and friction. HK pioneered this use of polymer materials in the production of handguns more than 30 years ago with the development of the VP70Z and P9S pistols.

The USP control lever, a combination safety and decocking lever, is frame mounted and quickly accessible, unlike the slide-mounted safeties common on many semi-automatic pistols.

Using a modified Browning-type action with a special patented recoil reduction system, the USP recoil reduction system reduces recoil effects on pistol components and also lowers the recoil forces felt by the shooter. This same recoil reduction system has been tested and proven in the HK Mark 23 pistol developed for the U.S. Special Operations Command. The USP recoil reduction system is insensitive to ammunition types and requires no special adjustment or maintenance. It functions effectively in all USP models.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Man Cave art piece
postcontent:
Man Cave art piece - one of a kind.                                                    .

Real Aircraft "nose art", complete and self-contained on the front cargo door of a 1940's Lockheed aircraft.  Genuine. This is NOT a re-creation. It's from an actual, crashed aircraft.

Items of this nature are very hard to find. If they survived a crash, they are usually exquisitely hard to remove intact. This one is completely contained on the cargo door of the Lockheed. It survived it's crash with just a bottom dent - which adds immeasurably to its character.

The piece depicts a cigar-chomping, stinger-forward - Wasp. He's looks like he's had a very bad day, he's holding a Tommy Gun and binocs, all on a red, white and blue banner.   The lettering "MILE HIGH HONEY" is a vibrant yellow, and the aluminum background metal has a clean, high-level shine. 

Impressive, colorful and ready to hang. It retains it's T-shape door handle and hinge tabs, and both were professionally finished on it's backside. Size is about 3 feet X 3 1/2 feet and about four-to-five inches thick (hollow-frame / aluminum structure).

For home rec-room, office, man-cave or business accent piece. It's very lightweight for what it is, and easily transportable. You could hang it with just one good-size nail. There are no sharp edges as the door was originally made with both rolled-edges and finished ones all around.

Photo available

An un-beatable conversation piece.
